    {front:"B12 — absorption and storage pathway", back:"Binds R protein in the stomach, transfers to intrinsic factor (IF) in the duodenum, is absorbed in the small intestine, and delivered via transcobalamin II. Stored in the liver as transcobalamin III; storage lasts 1–2 years."},
    {front:"B12 deficiency — neuropsychiatric symptoms and mechanism", back:"Peripheral neuropathy, dementia, psychiatric changes, optic atrophy — caused by methylmalonic acid (MMA) accumulation, which impairs myelination."},
    {front:"Distinguishing B12 vs folate deficiency when unclear", back:"Check MMA and total homocysteine (tHcys). High levels of both are indicative of low B12; an isolated high tHcys (normal MMA) is indicative of folate deficiency."},
    {front:"B12 deficiency — treatment and response", back:"Cyanocobalamin 1mg IM, once daily for a week → once weekly for 2–8 weeks → once monthly. Response: reticulocytosis within a few days, hemoglobin rise after 10 days, transient hypokalemia."},
    {front:"Folic acid deficiency — definition, causes, and findings", back:"Folate <2. Causes: low fruit/vegetable intake, pregnancy, methotrexate (an antifolate). Symptoms: paleness, jaundice, glossitis, pancytopenia. Smear: hypersegmented neutrophils, severe macrocytosis (>150), macro-leukocytic precursors."},
    {front:"Folic acid deficiency — treatment", back:"PO folic acid, 1–5mg once daily for 1–4 months."},
    {front:"Hemolytic anemia — congenital causes", back:"Hereditary spherocytosis (AD), hereditary elliptocytosis (AD), G6PD deficiency (X-linked), sickle cell anemia."},
    {front:"Warm AIHA — mechanism and smear findings", back:"Caused by IgG with a negative C3 result. Causes spherocytes and partial phagocytosis (bite cells). Associated with CLL, drug reactions, lymphoma, SLE."},
    {front:"Cold AIHA — mechanism and smear findings", back:"Caused by IgM with a positive C3 result. Causes intravascular hemolysis with schistocytes. Associated with mononucleosis, paroxysmal cold hemoglobinuria (PCH)."},
    {front:"Non-immune hemolytic anemia — causes", back:"Microangiopathic hemolytic anemia (MAHA: HUS, TTP, DIC), infections (malaria, Clostridium), renal disease, splenomegaly."},
    {front:"Coombs test — direct vs indirect", back:"Direct Coombs: patient RBCs incubated with serum — detects AIHA and post-transfusion hemolytic response. Indirect Coombs: patient serum introduced to commercial RBCs with known antigens — used for antibody screening/typing (e.g. pre-transfusion, pregnancy)."},
    {front:"Hemolytic anemia — general treatment", back:"Folic acid, treat the underlying cause (drug, infection, immunosuppression), blood transfusion if needed."},
    {front:"Anemia of chronic disease — mechanism", back:"Mild hypoproliferative anemia driven by cytokines (IL-1, IFN-gamma, TNF-alpha) in chronic inflammation. Hepcidin, secreted by the liver during chronic inflammation, blocks iron release from macrophages and reduces intestinal iron absorption, lowering iron access despite adequate stores."},
    {front:"Anemia of chronic disease — treatment", back:"Treat the primary cause; blood transfusion or subcutaneous EPO if needed."}
